#. </h1></div><p>
#. <a class="pts-vp-pli" id="pts-vp-pli3.252"></a>
#. <a class="sc" id="sc1"></a>
msgctxt "an5.211:1.1"
msgid ""
"“Yo so, bhikkhave, bhikkhu akkosakaparibhāsako ariyūpavādī sabrahmacārīnaṃ, "
"tassa pañca ādīnavā pāṭikaṅkhā."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "an5.211:1.2"
msgid "Katame pañca?"
msgstr ""

# chinnaparipantha is apparently unique. BB has “cuts of the outlet”. But paripantha has no attested meaning as “outlet”. The PTS dict does mention this, and gives a couple of refs, but it seems to be mistaken, as neither of these in fact support the reading. Nor is that meaning found in MW: http://sanskritdictionary.com/?iencoding=iast&q=paripantha&lang=sans&action=Search But if we take the normal meaning of paripantha, how is a parajika to “cut off the obstacle”. I propose reading as a dvanda: chinno paripantho. Also note that in this passage the vā only is used for the first three items, which might suggest the last two were added.
#. VAR: chinnaparipantho → chinnaparibandho (mr)
msgctxt "an5.211:1.3"
msgid ""
"Pārājiko vā hoti chinnaparipantho, aññataraṃ vā saṃkiliṭṭhaṃ āpattiṃ "
"āpajjati, bāḷhaṃ vā rogātaṅkaṃ phusati, sammūḷho kālaṃ karoti, kāyassa bhedā "
"paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "an5.211:1.4"
msgid ""
"Yo so, bhikkhave, bhikkhu akkosakaparibhāsako ariyūpavādī sabrahmacārīnaṃ, "
"tassa ime pañca ādīnavā pāṭikaṅkhā”ti."
msgstr ""

#. </p><p class="endsection">
msgctxt "an5.211:1.5"
msgid "Paṭhamaṃ."
msgstr ""
